\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Project Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The project focuses on a multi-agent system where autonomous vehicles work together to optimize urban mobility and traffic coordination,
 using smart intersections.
 The goal is to improve traffic flow,
 reduce congestion,
 and enhance safety,
 with all autonomous vehicles working toward a shared objective:
 reaching their destination in the shortest time possible,
 while adhering to traffic laws and ensuring safety of all vehicles and pedestrians.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
High-Level System Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Coordination among autonomous vehicles to avoid congestion and delays,
 while taking into account that not all entities are autonomous agents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Implementation of optimal "wait and go" strategies at intersections and during lane merges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Application of Game Theory to find the best strategies for decision-making.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Real-time decision-making in extreme circumstances,
 such as system failures,
 emergencies,
 accidents,
 or bad weather.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prioritizing emergency vehicles with minimal cost to civilian vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Scope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The system operates in a virtual or simulated smart urban environment,
 where vehicles and smart intersections work together to manage traffic flow.
 The focus is on the behavior of autonomous vehicles and interactions at smart intersections rather than the physical aspects of the vehicles themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The project will not cover aspects like vehicle hardware but will focus on agent behavior and coordination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The project will take into account the existence of human driven vehicles and of pedestrians,
 including their ability to behave unexpectedly,
 but the system metrics will exclude accidents that are caused solely by human behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The project will not cover any reports to the authorities regarding traffic law violations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Environment Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment is urban and complex,
 consisting of autonomous vehicles,
 smart intersections,
 traffic signals,
 and road signs.
 Vehicles interact with each other and the infrastructure (smart intersections) to optimize traffic flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Physical/Logical Boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system operates in a simulated urban environment,
 where autonomous vehicles interact with smart intersections and each other.
 The focus is on traffic management rather than physical road layouts.
 The environment will also consider extreme weather conditions and emergency situations,
 as well as uncontrollable pedestrians and human driven vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Important Features
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment includes urban traffic,
 traffic signs,
 smart traffic signals,
 and real-time interactions between autonomous vehicles and intersections.
 It is designed to handle variable traffic conditions and optimize the flow while maintaining safety for all entities involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-agent entities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment includes pedestrians and human driven vehicles which are non autonomous,
 we have to consider them as a dynamic part of the environment,
 as they cannot be communicated with in the same way autonomous vehicles can.
 Pedestrians and human driven vehicles are not agents in this project,
 they are parts of the environment which are not completely predictable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Emergency vehicles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The environment includes emergency vehicles that must be prioritized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Agent Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Agent Types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Autonomous
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Vehicle:
 Each autonomous vehicle is an autonomous agent.
 Each vehicle is responsible for navigating through the urban environment,
 making decisions on when to speed up,
 slow down,
 stop,
 and when to interact with other autonomous vehicles at intersections.
 It must also decide when to interact with pedestrians and human driven vehicles using classic signaling,
 hazard lights and honking in cases of emergency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Smart
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Intersection:
 Each intersection is also an agent that manages the flow of traffic at the intersection,
 ensuring that vehicles and pedestrians pass through safely and efficiently according to traffic rules,
 and that emergency vehicles are prioritized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Agent Goals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Autonomous
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Vehicle:
 The vehicle’s goal is to reach its destination in the shortest time possible while maintaining safety and adhering to traffic laws.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Smart
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Intersection:
 The intersection’s goal is to optimize traffic flow by minimizing wait times and ensuring the safe passage of vehicles and pedestrians.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Perception and Action Capabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Autonomous
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Vehicle:
 Each vehicle senses its environment,
 including traffic conditions,
 road signs,
 traffic lights,
 and the state of pedestrians and other vehicles,
 autonomous and human driven.
 It makes decisions based on this information.
 In case of a visible vehicle that is not recognized as autonomous,
 positioning is very important as human drivers' vision is more limited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Smart
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Intersection:
 The intersection perceives traffic conditions and optimizes signal timings to improve traffic flow and reduce congestion.
 It takes into account that not all vehicles are autonomous,
 and it cannot rely only on radio signals from the autonomous vehicle for information.
 It must include sensors that can detect pedestrians and human driven vehicles as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Functional Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Autonomous
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Vehicle
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Requirements:
 Each vehicle must be able to perceive the environment (traffic conditions,
 road signs,
 signals) and make decisions accordingly.
 It must react to changes in traffic flow,
 road conditions,
 and other vehicles.
 Each should signal to the intersection control system using radio waves and receive information from it the same way.
 It must be aware of the existence of all surrounding vehicles,
 autonomous and human driven.
 Any vehicle that does not signal being autonomous is considered human driven and is treated accordingly (blind spots,
 possibility of unexpected behaviors,
 inability to communicate using radio waves,
 etc.).
 It must also be aware of pedestrians and take them into consideration,
 including their limitations and abilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Smart
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Intersection
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Requirements:
 Each smart intersection must optimize traffic flow by adjusting signal timings,
 managing vehicle passage,
 and ensuring safe and efficient passage through the intersection.
 Each must communicate with the smart vehicles using radio waves and must be aware of smart and human driven vehicles.
 It must also let pedestrians pass in a reasonable time and prioritize emergency vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
System-Level
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Requirements:
 The system must work collaboratively,
 with all agents coordinating to reduce delays and prevent accidents.
 Decision-making must adhere to all traffic laws and optimize traffic flow.
 It must take all non-agent entities into account as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Real-Time
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Decision
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Making:
 The system must be able to make real-time decisions in extreme situations,
 such as accidents,
 sudden weather changes,
 or technical failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulation & Visualization Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Real-Time Traffic Display
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation must show vehicles in real-time,
 displaying their movements,
 decisions,
 and interactions with other vehicles and intersections.
 It must also show pedestrians and human driven vehicles that might have unpredictable behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Extreme Situation Simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation should also show how the system handles extreme conditions,
 such as bad weather or unexpected system failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Strategy Tracking
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation must demonstrate how “wait and go” strategies are applied in real-time at intersections and during lane merges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Non-agent entities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation must include pedestrians and human driven vehicles,
 and be aware of their limited ability to communicate and their possibly unexpected behavior.
 They must be shown and be able to behave in ways the system can't fully predict.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Emergency vehicles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation should include emergency vehicles that must be prioritized over civilian vehicles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interaction Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Voting Strategies:
 At intersections or during lane merges,
 vehicles will use voting strategies to determine the order of passage based on priority or rules defined by the intersection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Traffic Rules:
 The system must adhere to predefined traffic rules,
 including stop signs,
 traffic lights,
 and other legal requirements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cooperation Between Agents:
 Autonomous vehicles will cooperate to optimize traffic flow,
 avoid congestion,
 and reduce delays.
 For example,
 vehicles might communicate with each other to ensure smooth transitions at busy intersections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The interactions with non-agent entities is extremely limited and must follow a strict set of rules defined by the traffic laws.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any emergency vehicle on duty outvote pedestrian vehicles at any time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Utility & Success Metrics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Success Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Success is defined as the ability to reach a destination in 110% of the time it would take a human driver who fully obeys the law,
 at most,
 while maintaining safety and without violating any traffic laws or causing accidents.
 Any traffic law violation is considered an unequivocal failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The metrics will specifically exclude any hazards or accidents caused solely by human behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The metrics will take into account emergency vehicles prioritizing,
 which may slow down civilian vehicles.
 With that said,
 this delay should also be minimized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Utility Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The system should optimize for the shortest travel time,
 minimizing delays and ensuring safety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The goal is to maximize the overall efficiency of traffic flow while adhering to traffic regulations.
 It should consider the possible roads' congestion and be able to make decisions based on all available knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It should try to predict the behavior of human driven vehicles and of pedestrians,
 while considering their ability to behave unexpectedly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Validation Scenarios
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 1:
 Vehicles approach a smart intersection with multiple vehicles arriving at the same time,
 some of them are human driven.
 The system must ensure that the autonomous vehicles pass through efficiently and reach their destination in the defined success time (Subsection 7.1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 2:
 The system must handle extreme weather conditions (e.g.,
 heavy rain or fog).
 The vehicles must continue to operate safely and efficiently despite reduced visibility or road conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 3:
 A scenario with heavy traffic congestion where vehicles must merge into a single lane.
 The system must ensure smooth merging and minimize traffic jams,
 while also adhering to traffic rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 4:
 Human driven vehicles and pedestrians are behaving unexpectedly and the system must be aware and careful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scenario 5:
 The traffic is flowing and the agents must still obey the law,
 the vehicles can't exceed the speed limit even if no one is around.
\end_layout

